{{Infobox software | name = Mapnik | logo = Mapnik logo.svg | screenshot = | caption = the core of geospatial visualization & processing | author = Artem Pavlenko | developer = The Mapnik Contributors | latest release version = 3.0.20<ref>{{cite web|title=Release 3.0.20|url=https://github.com/mapnik/mapnik/blob/v3.0.20/CHANGELOG.md#3013|accessdate=June 12, 2018}}</ref> | latest release date = {{Start date and age|2018|04|20}} | programming language = [[C++]] | operating system = [[Cross-platform]] | size = | genre = | license = [[GNU Lesser General Public License|LGPL]] | website = {{Official URL}} }} '''Mapnik''' is an [[open-source software|open-source]] [[Cartography|mapping]] toolkit for desktop and server based map [[Rendering (computer graphics)|rendering]], written in [[C++]]. Artem Pavlenko, the original developer of Mapnik, set out with the explicit goal of creating beautiful maps<ref name=beautmaps>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060203025457/http://mapnik.org/faq/ Beautiful Maps as an explicit goal in the Mapnik FAQ]</ref> by employing the [[Sub-pixel resolution|sub-pixel]] anti-aliasing of the [[Anti-Grain Geometry]] (AGG) library. Mapnik now also has a [[Cairo (graphics)|Cairo]] rendering backend. For handling common software tasks such as memory management, [[file system]] access, regular expressions, and XML parsing, Mapnik utilizes the [[Boost C++ libraries]]. An [[XML]] file can be used to define a collection of mapping objects that determine the appearance of a map, or objects can be constructed programmatically in C++, Python, and [[Node.js]].
==Data Format== A number of data formats are supported in Mapnik using a plugin framework. Current plugins exist that utilize [[GDAL|OGR]] and [[GDAL]] to read a range of vector and raster datasets. Mapnik also has custom [[Shapefile]], [[PostGIS]] and [[GeoTIFF]] readers. More data access plug-ins will be available in the future. There is also an osm2pgsql utility,<ref name=osm2pgsql>{{cite web|url=http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Osm2pgsql|title=Osm2pgsql}}</ref> that converts [[OpenStreetMap]] data into a format that can be loaded into [[PostgreSQL]]. Mapnik can then be used to render the OSM data into maps with the appearance the user wants.
==Platforms== Mapnik is a cross platform toolkit that runs on Windows, Mac, [[Unix-like]] systems like Linux and Solaris (since release 0.4).
==Usage== One of its many users is the [[OpenStreetMap]] project (OSM), which uses it in combination with an [[Apache Web Server]] module (mod_tile) and openstreetmap-carto style to render tiles that make up the OSM default layer.<ref name=slippy>[http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Mapnik OpenStreetMap's main Slippy Map layer]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mapnik|url=http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Mapnik|publisher=OpenStreetMap Wiki}}</ref> Mapnik is also used by CloudMade,<ref>{{cite web|title=CloudMade|url=http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/CloudMade#Technical|publisher=OpenStreetMap Wiki}}</ref> [[MapQuest]],<ref>{{cite web|title=MapQuest Mapnik Style|url=https://github.com/MapQuest/MapQuest-Mapnik-Style|publisher=GitHub}}</ref> and [[MapBox]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mapnik Performance|url=http://developmentseed.org/blog/2010/oct/19/qa-mapnik-performance-just-important-its-beauty|publisher=Development Seed}}</ref>
==License== Mapnik is free software and is released under [[LGPL]] (GNU Lesser General Public Licence).
