{{Other uses|Sawran (disambiguation)}}
{{coord|43|30|55|N|67|46|7|E|region:KK|display=title}} {{Infobox ancient site |name = Sawran |native_name = Сауран |alternate_name = Sauran |image = Sawran, Kazakhstan 03.jpg |alt = |caption = Part of the ancient city wall of Sawran |map = |map_type = |map_alt = |map_size = |location = Southern Kazakhstan oblast |region = |coordinates = {{coord|43.515278|67.768611|display=inline}} |type = |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = 6th century CE |abandoned = 1515 CE |epochs = |cultures = |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = 20th century |archaeologists = |condition = ruin |ownership = |public_access = |website = |notes = }}
'''Sawran''' or '''Sauran''' ({{lang-kk|Сауран|translit=Saýran}}, {{IPA-kk|sɑwˈrɑn|pron}}) is an ancient city located {{convert|43|km}} north-west of the city of [[Turkistan (city)|Turkistan]] in [[South Kazakhstan Region|Southern Kazakhstan]], near the river [[Syr Darya]].
One of the earliest mentions of the city comes from the Arab geographer [[Al-Muqaddasi]], who described it in the 10th century as "a large city surrounded by seven walls, mosque located in the inner city."<ref name=SilkRoad>{{cite web|url=https://moluch.ru/archive/141/39727/|title=The Sauran town of the silk way road|author=Abdrassilov Berikbay Kurmanbaevich|date=16 Feb 2017|accessdate=27 Aug 2017}}</ref> In 1065, the city submitted to the [[Seljuq dynasty]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.282460/2015.282460.Turkestan-Down#page/n331/mode/2up/search/sawran|title=Turkestan Down To The Mongol Invasion|author=W. Barthold|page=314|accessdate=27 Aug 2017}}</ref> which was part of the transformation of the [[Kara-Khanid Khanate]] into a vassal of the Seljuqs.
Around the 1370s, when the region was under the control of [[Urus Khan]], [[Tokhtamysh]] of the blue horde, heavily supported by [[Amir Timur]], tried to conquer the region, aiming to rule the cities of Sawran, [[Otrar]], Saganac, [[Sayram (city)|Seiram]], Serai, and others.<ref>{{cite book|title=History of the Mongols from the 9th to the 19th Century: The So-Called Tartars of Russia and Central Asia|author=Henry Hoyle Howorth|page=222|date=1 Jan 2008|accessdate=27 Aug 2017}}</ref> The city provided the brick and tile for the construction of [[Mausoleum of Khoja Ahmed Yasawi]], which was commissioned by [[Amir Timur]] in 1389; the mausoleum is 25 miles from the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electrummagazine.com/2014/03/khoja-ahmad-yasawi-and-his-mausoleum/|title=Khoja Ahmad Yasawi and His Mausoleum|publisher=Electrum Magazine|author=Aigerim Korzhumbayeva|date=3 Mar 2014|accessdate=27 Aug 2017}}</ref>
By the 15th century, the city had established diplomatic relations with the [[Ming dynasty]], which recorded the name of the city in the [[Ming Shilu]] as 掃蘭 (saolan).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eacrh.net/ojs/index.php/crossroads/article/view/41/Vol8_Kenzheakhmet_html|title=The Qazaq Khanate as Documented in Ming Dynasty Sources|publisher=Crossroads: Studies on the History of Exchange Relations in the East Asian world|author=Nurlan Kenzheakhmet|year=2013|accessdate=27 Aug 2017}}</ref> The poet Zayn al-Din Mahmud Vasifi visited the city from 1514-1515, and described the city's [[Qanat|karez]] water infrastructure.<ref name=SilkRoad />
Like [[Otrar]], the city suffered with the decline of [[Silk Road]], and struggles for power in the region.
